  "prompt": "What are the abbreviations for degrees?",
  "response": "The term \"degrees\" can refer to different concepts depending on the context. Below are the common abbreviations for **academic degrees** and **degree measurements** (such as angles and temperature):\n\n---\n\n### 1. Academic Degree Abbreviations\n\nAcademic degrees are awarded by educational institutions and are typically abbreviated using initials and periods. Here's a list of common degrees and their standard abbreviations:\n\n#### **Associate Degrees**\n- **Associate of Arts**: **A.A.**\n- **Associate of Science**: **A.S.**\n- **Associate of Applied Science**: **A.A.S.**\n\n#### **Bachelor's Degrees**\n- **Bachelor of Arts**: **B.A.**\n- **Bachelor of Science**: **B.S.** or **B.Sc.**\n- **Bachelor of Fine Arts**: **B.F.A.**\n- **Bachelor of Business Administration**: **B.B.A.**\n- **Bachelor of Engineering**: **B.Eng.**\n- **Bachelor of Education**: **B.Ed.**\n\n#### **Master's Degrees**\n- **Master of Arts**: **M.A.**\n- **Master of Science**: **M.S.** or **M.Sc.**\n- **Master of Fine Arts**: **M.F.A.**\n- **Master of Business Administration**: **M.B.A.**\n- **Master of Engineering**: **M.Eng.**\n- **Master of Education**: **M.Ed.**\n\n#### **Doctoral Degrees**\n- **Doctor of Philosophy**: **Ph.D.**\n- **Doctor of Education**: **Ed.D.**\n- **Doctor of Medicine**: **M.D.**\n- **Doctor of Dental Surgery**: **D.D.S.**\n- **Doctor of Veterinary Medicine**: **D.V.M.**\n- **Doctor of Laws**: **LL.D.**\n- **Doctor of Nursing Practice**: **D.N.P.**\n\n#### **Professional Degrees**\n- **Juris Doctor**: **J.D.**\n- **Bachelor of Laws**: **LL.B.**\n- **Master of Public Health**: **M.P.H.**\n- **Master of Social Work**: **M.S.W.**\n\n---\n\n### 2. Degree Measurements Abbreviations\n\nDegrees are also units of measurement used in various fields, such as geometry, geography, and meteorology. Here are the standard abbreviations:\n\n#### **Angle Measurements**\n- **Degree**: **\u00b0**\n  - Example: 90\u00b0 (read as \"90 degrees\")\n- **Minute**: **\u2032**\n  - 1 degree = 60 minutes\n- **Second**: **\u2033**\n  - 1 minute = 60 seconds\n\n#### **Temperature Measurements**\n- **Degrees Celsius**: **\u00b0C**\n  - Example: 25\u00b0C\n- **Degrees Fahrenheit**: **\u00b0F**\n  - Example: 77\u00b0F\n- **Degrees Kelvin**: While Kelvin is technically an absolute temperature scale and not expressed in \"degrees,\" it is sometimes informally referred to with the degree symbol:\n  - **Kelvin**: **K**\n  - Example: 300 K\n\n---\n\n### **Usage Notes**\n\n- **Academic degrees** are usually written with periods after each letter (e.g., B.A., M.Sc.).\n- **Degree measurements** use the degree symbol (\u00b0) without periods and are typically placed before the \"C\" for Celsius or \"F\" for Fahrenheit.\n- Avoid confusion by capitalizing academic degree abbreviations when they precede a name (e.g., **Dr. Jane Smith, Ph.D.**) and using lowercase when they follow a name (e.g., **Jane Smith, Ph.D.**).\n\n---\n\nIf you have a specific type of degree abbreviation in mind or need further details, feel free to ask!",
